Day 02 - Linux File Management
Introduction

Linux stores everything as files and directories. Understanding file management is one of the most important skills for a DevOps Engineer because every server, application, Docker container, Kubernetes deployment, and configuration file relies on the Linux filesystem.
Linux Filesystem Structure

Linux starts from a root directory:

/

Everything in Linux exists under this root directory.
Important Directories
/home

Stores user files and personal data.

Example:

/home/ubuntu

Contains:

    Documents

    Downloads

    Projects

    Scripts

/etc

Stores system configuration files.

Examples:

/etc/passwd
/etc/ssh/sshd_config

Used by administrators and system services.
/var

Stores variable and changing data.

Examples:

    Logs

    Cache

    Databases

/var/log

/tmp

Stores temporary files.

Files may be removed automatically after reboot.
/bin

Contains essential Linux commands.

Examples:

ls
cp
mv
cat

/usr

Stores installed applications and software.
/dev

Represents hardware devices as files.

Examples:

/dev/sda
/dev/tty

/proc

Contains information about running processes and the Linux kernel.
Command: pwd
Purpose

Displays the current working directory.
Syntax

pwd

Example

pwd

Output:

/home/ubuntu

What Happens Internally?

Linux checks the shell's current directory location and prints it.
Use Cases

    Verify current location

    Avoid executing commands in the wrong directory

Command: ls
Purpose

Lists files and directories.
Syntax

ls

Example

ls

Output:

Documents Downloads Desktop

What Happens Internally?

Linux reads directory entries and displays their names.
ls -l

Displays detailed information.

ls -l

Example:

-rw-rw-r-- 1 ubuntu ubuntu 20 Jun 09 notes.txt

Shows:

    Permissions

    Owner

    Group

    File Size

    Modified Date

ls -la

Displays:

    Hidden files

    Detailed information

ls -la

Command: touch
Purpose

Creates an empty file.
Syntax

touch filename.txt

Example

touch notes.txt

Creates:

notes.txt

What Happens Internally?

    Linux checks if file exists.

    If not, creates an empty file.

    If it exists, updates the timestamp.

Use Cases

    Create configuration files

    Create scripts

    Create placeholders

Command: mkdir
Purpose

Creates directories.
Syntax

mkdir directory_name

Example

mkdir DevOps

Creates:

DevOps/

What Happens Internally?

Linux creates:

    Directory entry

    Metadata

    Inode

mkdir -p

Creates nested directories.

mkdir -p AWS/EKS/Cluster

Result:

AWS
└── EKS
    └── Cluster

Use Cases

    Project structures

    Kubernetes folders

    Terraform modules

Command: cat
Purpose

Displays file content.
Syntax

cat filename

Example

cat notes.txt

Output:

Hello DevOps

What Happens Internally?

    Opens the file.

    Reads data.

    Prints data to terminal.

Create File Using cat

cat > notes.txt

Type content and press:

CTRL + D

To save.
Command: echo
Purpose

Prints text.
Syntax

echo "Hello"

Output:

Hello

Write Content to File

echo "Hello DevOps" > notes.txt

Content:

Hello DevOps

Important

Single greater-than symbol (>)

echo "New Data" > notes.txt

Overwrites existing content.

Previous data is lost.
Append Content

echo "Second Line" >> notes.txt

Result:

Hello DevOps
Second Line

Double greater-than symbol (>>) appends content.
Command: cp
Purpose

Copies files and directories.
Syntax

cp source destination

Example

cp notes.txt backup.txt

Result:

notes.txt
backup.txt

Both files exist.
What Happens Internally?

    Opens source file.

    Reads data.

    Creates destination file.

    Writes copied data.

Copy Directory

cp -r Projects Backup

The -r option means recursive.

Copies all files and folders.
Command: mv
Purpose

Moves or renames files and directories.
Rename File

mv notes.txt linux.txt

Result:

linux.txt

Old filename disappears.
Move File

mv linux.txt DevOps/

Result:

DevOps/linux.txt

What Happens Internally?

Linux updates directory entries without copying file content.

This makes mv very fast.
Command: rm
Purpose

Deletes files and directories.
Delete File

rm notes.txt

Removes the file.
Delete Directory

rm -r Projects

Deletes:

Projects
├── file1
├── file2
└── folder

Everything inside is removed.
rm -rf

rm -rf Projects

Options:

-r = Recursive
-f = Force

Deletes everything without confirmation.
Warning

Never execute:

sudo rm -rf /

This can destroy the entire operating system.
Command: tree
Purpose

Displays folder structure visually.
Syntax

tree

Example

DevOps
├── Docker
│   └── notes.txt
└── Linux
    └── commands.txt

Why DevOps Engineers Use It

    Project documentation

    GitHub repositories

    Kubernetes manifests

    Terraform projects

    Docker project structures

Real DevOps Example

Project Structure:

kubernetes-projects
├── deployment.yaml
├── service.yaml
├── ingress.yaml

Verification:

tree kubernetes-projects

Ensures all files are organized before committing to GitHub.
Day 02 Summary
Command	Purpose
pwd	Show current directory
ls	List files and directories
touch	Create files
mkdir	Create directories
cat	Read file contents
echo	Display or write text
cp	Copy files/directories
mv	Move or rename files
rm	Delete files/directories
tree	Display directory structure
Key Takeaways

    Linux treats everything as a file.

    Directories organize files and folders.

    File management is a fundamental DevOps skill.

    Always verify before deleting with rm.

    Use tree to visualize project structures.

    Mastering these commands will make future DevOps topics easier.
